THOUGHT

I inspected the relevant storage growth code and reproduced the heap overflow with an input that first creates enough scalar variables to make `v_count` larger than the initial array capacity, then creates enough arrays to cross `a_count`. ASan reports an out-of-bounds write into `a_names` at `bc/util.c:577`, with the allocation coming from the initial `more_arrays()` call. The reported write is the first visible symptom: `lookup()` stores the array name before growing the arrays/name tables. The deeper corruption described in `more_arrays()` is confirmed in source: it allocates `arrays` and `a_names` using `a_count`, but initializes `arrays[indx]` until `indx < v_count`. If scalar variable growth has made `v_count > a_count`, `more_arrays()` writes past the newly allocated `arrays` buffer. The exact local bug is the wrong count variable in `bc/storage.c`.

ROOT CAUSE: `bc/storage.c:176` in `more_arrays()` uses `v_count` as the upper bound when initializing newly allocated array slots: `for (; indx < v_count; indx++) arrays[indx] = NULL;`. But this function allocated `arrays` and `a_names` to `a_count` elements at lines 166-168. After many scalar variables, `v_count` can exceed `a_count`; then growing arrays initializes past the end of the `arrays` allocation, corrupting heap redzones/metadata or adjacent heap objects. The reproduced ASan trace also exposes a related ordering bug in `bc/util.c:577-581`: `a_names[id->a_name] = name` occurs before checking `id->a_name >= a_count` and calling `more_arrays()`, so the name table can be written one element past its allocation at the growth boundary. Both arise from treating separate storage capacities as interchangeable/manual globals.

LOCAL FIX: Minimal fix for the specified overflow is to initialize only the allocated array capacity:
```diff
--- a/bc/storage.c
+++ b/bc/storage.c
@@ -173,7 +173,7 @@ more_arrays ()


   /* Initialize the new elements. */
-  for (; indx < v_count; indx++)
+  for (; indx < a_count; indx++)
     arrays[indx] = NULL;
```
Additionally, to remove the boundary overflow observed by ASan in `lookup()`, grow before storing the new array name:
```diff
--- a/bc/util.c
+++ b/bc/util.c
@@ -573,13 +573,13 @@ lookup (name, namekind)
           return (-id->a_name);
         }
       id->a_name = next_array++;
-      a_names[id->a_name] = name;
       if (id->a_name < MAX_STORE)
         {
           if (id->a_name >= a_count)
             more_arrays ();
+          a_names[id->a_name] = name;
           return (-id->a_name);
         }
```

GLOBAL FIX: Replace the parallel global raw arrays plus independent `*_count` globals with a single typed growable table abstraction per namespace, e.g. `struct storage_table { void **items; char **names; size_t len; size_t cap; }`, with one `ensure_capacity(table, index)` API that grows, copies, and zero-initializes both `items` and `names` together before any indexed write. Callers should not directly compare or mutate `a_count`, `v_count`, `f_count`, or write `*_names[index]` before capacity checks. This removes copy/paste growth loops, prevents using another namespace's capacity as a bound, and centralizes invariants such as `index < cap` and “name/item arrays have the same capacity.” A debug build assertion in the accessor (`assert(index < table->cap)`) and ASan/UBSan regression tests covering growth boundaries for variables, arrays, and functions would catch this class of capacity mismatch immediately.

